{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ψεῦδος</b>, εος, τό, <br /> <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>dative</i> <i>plural</i> ψεύδεσσι, see at {ψευδής} I.2: (ψεύδω):— <b>falsehood, lie,</b> ψεύδεα.. ἐτύμοισιν ὁμοῖα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 19.203, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Theogonia” 27; ψεῦδός κεν φαῖμεν 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.81; ψεῦδος δ᾽ οὐκ ἐρέει 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.20 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; εἴ τε ψεῦδος ὑπόσχεσις εἴ τε καὶ οὐκί whether the promise be a <b>lie</b> or no, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 2.349; οὔτι ψεῦδος ἐμὰς ἄτας κατέλεξας 9.115; ψεύδεσσιν θέλγειν τινά 21.276, compare 23.576, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.387; οὐ ψεύδεϊ τέγξω λόγον 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 4.19 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ψ. ποικίλα, αἰόλον ψ., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “O.” 1.29, “N.” 8.25 \">Refs</a>]; ψ. γλυκύ a sweet <b>deceit,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “P.” 2.37; ψεῦδος οὐδὲν ὧν λέγω 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Electra” 1220; οὐδὲν ἕρπει ψ. εἰς γῆρας χρόνου [prev. author] “fragment” 62; εἴ τι ψεῦδος εἴρηκα 5th c.BC: Antipho Orator 3.4.2; ψ. ἐπιφέρειν 4th c.BC: Aeschines Orator 3.41: ψ. λέγειν distinguished from ψεύδεσθαι, “Stoicorum Veterum Fragmenta” 2.42. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> in Logic, <b>false conclusion, fallacy,</b> συλλογισμὸς τοῦ ψεύδους [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Analytica Priora” 61b3 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; συμβαίνει ψ.[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 37a36:\">Refs</a>] —in “NT”  of what is opposed to religious truth, <b>false doctrine,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"NT.Rom.1.25\">NT</a>]; ποιῶν βδέλυγμα καὶ ψ., i.e. doing what is repugnant to the true faith, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Rev.21.27 \">NT</a>]; of false anatomical doctrine, τὸ οἴεσθαι.. ψ. ἐστι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Soranus Medicus 1.17. \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 12.24 ψεύδεα\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>] are <b>spots, pimples</b> on the nose; supposed to be characteristic of liars, cf. Scholia (at [prev. work]); compare ψυδράκιον. <br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>white spots</b> on the fingernails, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.AD: Alexander Aphrodisiensis Philosophus “προβλήματα ἀνέκδοτα” 2.58. \">Refs 3rd c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> In [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus ψεῦδος is frequently opposed to ἀληθές, “Grg.” 505e, “R.” 382d, “Euthd.” 272b, +others\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; so almost like an <i>adjective</i> (compare ψευδής [near the start]), ὄνομα ψεῦδος καὶ ἀληθὲς λέγειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Cra.” 385c; παράδοξόν τε καὶ ψεῦδος ὄνομα “Plt.” 281b: compare 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Heraclidae” 462 codices \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G5579","accentedUnicode":"ψεῦδος","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G0893","matchingForm":"ἀψευδής","stepTransliteration":"apseudēs","gloss":"not a liar","_zh_tw_Gloss":"無謊言","_es_Gloss":"no mentiroso","_zh_Gloss":"无谎言"},{"strongNumber":"G5570","matchingForm":"ψευδαπόστολος","stepTransliteration":"pseudapostolos","gloss":"false apostle","_zh_tw_Gloss":"假使徒","_es_Gloss":"falso apóstol","_zh_Gloss":"假使徒"},{"strongNumber":"G5571","matchingForm":"ψευδής","stepTransliteration":"pseudēs","gloss":"false","_zh_tw_Gloss":"說謊, 是假","_es_Gloss":"falso","_zh_Gloss":"说谎, 是假"},{"strongNumber":"G5573","matchingForm":"ψευδολόγος","stepTransliteration":"pseudologos","gloss":"lying","_zh_tw_Gloss":"說謊","_es_Gloss":"mentiroso","_zh_Gloss":"说谎"},{"strongNumber":"G5574","matchingForm":"ψεύδομαι","stepTransliteration":"pseudomai","gloss":"to lie","_zh_tw